s all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, which is presumably a major Iranian airspace region. Exceptions are limited. That sounds like it qualifies as a broad closure with limited exceptions, which per rule is okay.\n\nHowever, there is also evidence that the NOTAM is about airport operations, not about overflight routes; but the rule's phrase \"commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\" could be satisfied by closure of airports that serve as nodes for arrival/departure, thus effectively closing commercial flights to/from those airports. It also says \"overflight\" but not necessarily required.\n\nBut there are arguments that the evidence does not prove complete suspension at two listed airports; indeed, the NOTAM indicates that some airports remain operational (sunrise-to-sunset, with fresh approval). That's not a complete suspension, but perhaps the alternative pathway (broad region) is satisfied.\n\nThe standard is preponderance: which side is more likely? We need to decide \"demonstrated\" if the proposition is more likely true; \"not_demonstrated\" if not.\n\nThe plaintiff has a strong argument that the NOTAM demonstrates a broad closure of a major airspace region (the western part of the Tehran FIR) and that limited exceptions are allowed. The defendant points out that the raw NOTAM does not specifically mention overflight route closures and that the exceptions are not negligible. Also that there is no official source, only secondary reports.\n\nConsidering the totality, I think the plaintiff has a fairly compelling case: they have the NOTAM text that shows a closure of \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR\" with only a limited number of exceptions, which fits \"broad closure\" with \"limited exceptions.\" That likely qualifies as a major closure within the rule's definition. The defendant's evidence is weaker: it has the NOTAM aggregated and a denial, but the NOTAM