/from those airports. It also says \"overflight\" but not necessarily required.\n\nBut there are arguments that the evidence does not prove complete suspension at two listed airports; indeed, the NOTAM indicates that some airports remain operational (sunrise-to-sunset, with fresh approval). That's not a complete suspension, but perhaps the alternative pathway (broad region) is satisfied.\n\nThe standard is preponderance: which side is more likely? We need to decide \"demonstrated\" if the proposition is more likely true; \"not_demonstrated\" if not.\n\nThe plaintiff has a strong argument that the NOTAM demonstrates a broad closure of a major airspace region (the western part of the Tehran FIR) and that limited exceptions are allowed. The defendant points out that the raw NOTAM does not specifically mention overflight route closures and that the exceptions are not negligible. Also that there is no official source, only secondary reports.\n\nConsidering the totality, I think the plaintiff has a fairly compelling case: they have the NOTAM text that shows a closure of \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR\" with only a limited number of exceptions, which fits \"broad closure\" with \"limited exceptions.\" That likely qualifies as a major closure within the rule's definition. The defendant's evidence is weaker: it has the NOTAM aggregated and a denial, but the NOTAM itself is strong evidence of closure. The overall record indicates that there is no contradictory source that disproves the occurrence.\n\nThus, as a council member, I would vote \"demonstrated\", i.e., the proposition is demonstrated.\n\nNow we must produce a concise rationale of no more than three sentences. Something like: \"The admitted NOTAM text shows Iran closed all airports in the western Tehran FIR, a major airspace region, with only limited, approved exceptions, satisfying the rule's definition of a broad, non‑weather closure. The plaintiff's evidence therefore meets the preponderance standard.\" That's two sentences.\n\nNow we need to call `mcp` with `aar_submit_council_vote` tool using args string (JSON). According to instructions, we must call exactly with vote and rationale JSON string. Vote can be \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\". We'll use \"demonstrated\". Rationale as string.\n\nThus we will call:\n\n{\n  \"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\n  \"rationale\":\"The admitted NOTAM text shows Iran closed all airports in the western Tehran FIR, a major airspace region, with only limited, approved exceptions, satisfying the rule's definition of a broad, non‑weather closure.\"\n}\n\nNow we must format the tool call correctly: tool name is `aar_submit_council_vote` (unprefixed), but we need to use prefixed `aar_`? The instructions say: \"The AAR prompt and tool list use unprefixed names such as `submit_council_vote`; in Pi, call the corresponding `aar_submit_council_vote` tool through `mcp`.\" So we need to call tool name `aar_submit_council_vote` (no `aar_` prefix? Actually they said \"in Pi, call the corresponding `aar_submit_council_vote` tool through `mcp`\". So the tool name is `aar_submit_council_vote`. We'll pass that as the `tool` field. And the args is a JSON string of the arguments.\n\nThus we will produce a tool call: `mcp` with args string `{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The admitted NOTAM text shows Iran closed all airports in the western Tehran FIR, a major airspace region, with only limited, approved exceptions, satisfying the rule's definition of a broad, non‑weather closure.\"}`.\n\nMake sure to not include extra spaces? It's fine.\n\nNow we need to execute that tool call. Then after that, presumably the tool will return `ok:true`. Then we must report that vote was accepted and stop. But the instructions: \"After `aar_submit_council_vote` returns `ok: true`, report that your vote was accepted and stop. Do not call `aar_wait_for_opportunity` again after your vote is accepted.\" So we need to make the tool call, wait for a res